and Reconciliation Commission of Sierra Leone, <i>Witness to Truth: Report of&#13;&#13;
the TRCSL, </i>2004, volume 2, pp. 27-32. The Truth and Reconciliation&#13;&#13;
Commission (TRC), mandated under the 1999 Lomé Peace Accord, was&#13;&#13;
established to provide an impartial historical record of the conflict, promote&#13;&#13;
reconciliation and healing, and make recommendations aimed at preventing a&#13;&#13;
repetition of the violations committed. Efforts to establish the TRC were&#13;&#13;
spearheaded by the UN Mission in Sierra Leone and the Office of the United&#13;&#13;
Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights.</span>&#13;
      </p>&#13;
    </div>&#13;
    <div id="ftn4">&#13;
      <p>&#13;
        <a href="#_ftnref4" name="_ftn4" id="_ftn4">&#13;
          <span class="MsoFootnoteReference">&#13;
            <span>&#13;
              <span class="MsoFootnoteReference">&#13;
                <span>[4]</span>&#13;
              </span>&#13;
            </span>&#13;
          </span>&#13;
        </a>&#13;
        <span> Lansana&#13;&#13;
Gberie, <i>A Dirty War in West Africa: The RUF and the Destruction of Sierra&#13;&#13;
Leone </i>(Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 2005)<i>, </i>pp. 4-6.</span>&#13;
      </p>&#13;
    </div>&#13;
    <div id="ftn5">&#13;
